Iranian students are willing to die for their country’s nuclear program.
They formed a human shield.
Several hundred university students formed human shields around nuclear facilities in Iran.
With their gesture they want to express their support for their country’s nuclear program in the face of a possible Israeli attack.
The students set out to pray Tuesday afternoon in front of the facilities and then choreographed death slogans to the US and Israel.
Hundreds of university students trained human shields in the Iranian city of Isfahan on Tuesday around the nuclear technology center in which uranium is being worked.
They want to prove that they are willing to defend their country’s nuclear program with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), in a recent report, found that Iran, according to all indications, is seeking nuclear weapons.
In Israel, there is talk of a possible attack on Iranian nuclear facilities.
The students started praying at noon at the Isfahan nuclear facilities and then launched death slogans against the U.S. and Israel.
In the event of an attack, which would be aimed at paralyzing the Iranian nuclear program, according to Israeli sources, not only the Isfahan plant, but also the Natanz facilities, where uranium is enriched, would be reached.
Daily menu of an obese child: no built-in breakfast and dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with overweight, with overweight affecting 9% of the school population and obesity affecting 5%.
Obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It is again shown the importance of the environment where you grow for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obsessive children feed, for example, on nests at least twice as often as children from families with normal weight.
For dinner, more than 19% of obese people had eaten fried potatoes the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program “Obesity is not a coincidence.”
In families of overweight children there is no practice of sports, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and almost 900 children from all over the Czech Republic participated in the same.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th grade.
A proper diet and plenty of exercise in the family are determinants, which significantly decrease the number of overweight and even obese children.
“Only half of the children surveyed have answered that they have five daily meals according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, meal, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet,” one of the survey’s results found.
No breakfast but with built-in for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, the details are also important, such as having a set time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of schoolchildren’s families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each has its own breakfast.
But the worst thing was to discover that in 10% of the households nothing is breakfasted.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a proper daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children, crazy chips are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet refreshments daily (70%).
As a general rule, more than 40% of the children surveyed do sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make Your Diet
The next phase of the study allowed the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offerings according to their tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years from the point of view of a healthy diet are far from ideal."
His favorite foods include pasta, meat and sweets.
"It's especially alarming the popularity of sweet refreshments," the study's final report warns.
As the main food, the palm is taken from the pasta and the poultry meat is closely followed.
Practically, children always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Changing to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after completing the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was in many cases a significant change in favor of the principles of a healthy diet," the study results point out.
Attention is drawn, for example, to sweet refreshments, where many children would begin to prefer normal, running water.
Children would also more often choose poultry meat and fish for the main meal in the questionnaire and would restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
