In Need for Speed: The Run, you will be competing all over America.
<0xE2><0x80><0xA2> Review
A trip, in principle carefree, is complicated due to a series of improper carelessness from a routine trip during the morning shift.
To a certain extent it was able to meet expectations, but that is of no use if, in reality, it was not intended to do anything extraordinary.
The new release, to which The Run is added to the title, aroused high expectations even before its release.
It promised to give new air to the old Need for Speed racing saga and, as shown, appears as a game that should not end up being an action genre again.
We also felt curious to know what the inserted scenes would look like, where the main character descends from the car and walks on his own foot.
As is usually the case in the NFS series, the results did not vary much from what we expected.
There are races that may seem acceptable, but in the total computation you lose points due to absurd failures, which have already been appearing in the series for years.
In fact, they can’t even call mistakes, but rather it’s the incomprehensible misunderstanding of programmers.
The adventure begins very well.
He introduces you to a story whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he is offered to take part in an illegal race across America.
You're sitting at the wheel on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your mission is to get to New York first.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than fifty races.
From this it follows that each race takes place along a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
Thus, one does not even remotely have the feeling that the game always offers the same.
Some of the environments are even pleasing to the eye, although the technical level of the graphics is equivalent to previous deliveries of the series.
Therefore, it is nothing of the other world.
But the walk through the desert, the autumn landscape or the snow-capped high mountains produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, races are diversified from time to time by an atypical element.
Thus, for example, in the desert you will find a sandstorm that diminishes visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you must be careful not to bury an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There are only a few models, but that is enough.
For a moment, you try to advance a required number of rivals (normal in a classic race), then you try to save time (timed classic duel) and then you get a duel against a single opponent.
In the middle of all this sometimes comes the police, which only makes things even more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape from someone and you have to help him, always pressing the right button at the right time.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are quite a few landscapes in the game than you would expect (in particular there are only three).
But the end result is positive, because this element does not become annoying and, in the context already mentioned, it is one of the elements that make the game more interesting.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
That means that today is no longer a big deal, but it cannot be said to be bad.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you can look elsewhere.
But a race designed with enough action fits this driving style quite well, although we can find something better among the games of the competition.
So far, everything is fine.
But problems arise after a certain time.
Unlike the correct driving models, the same is no longer the case with collisions.
Games of this type can not be expected to recreate deformations and complicated collisions, but in fact before a hit against any object, you can not predict how your car will react, with which everything is not in order.
It is typical that, by making a very tight advance or circulating the car with normal traffic, there are only slight rocks, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up making uncontrolled pirouettes.
Or even completely destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, no big problems arise, but it can put you in a bad mood.
The resets are programmed in such a way that, when you suffer an accident or get out of the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, in each race only five resets are available.
If you consume all of them, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it’s nothing more than a help in case something goes wrong, but it’s not very reliable.
Sometimes, even the reset doesn’t help, it just helps you learn the given memory step.
A big drawback of the game is that the same facts are repeated in different places.
In some curves, for example, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, they are impossible to take.
Other times you find yourself somewhere "civil" vehicles always with the same configuration, even if you are the first, fifth or arrive five minutes before or after.
This makes you angry especially in situations, when you see that two cars going to meet in opposite directions, your opponent goes ahead without problems, but when you arrive, you have to turn or brake.
It doesn’t matter when you arrive, because it’s programmed that the “surprise” will always happen in front of your noses.
The opponents also have one more advantage.
Throughout the game you will arrive at sites where, regardless of the time, you will always be ahead of the same opponent on the same site.
In addition, this happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must arrive before you, at any price.
When it comes in front of you, it makes it difficult for you to see the cars coming in front, so at first you can pop the car.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so apparent that it will surely disappoint you right away.
And it is a pity, because even if the model of the trip is simple, the game is fun and action, so it is often not possible to follow in detail what happens or where.
And it really doesn’t matter, whether the merit gets the idea with fifty exclusive tracks or the qualifying in the race so it doesn’t get bored, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gas stations next to the road, because that’s where you have to change your car, although in the vast majority of cases you’ll have enough of what you have.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports are suitable for urban areas, American strong cars for straight highways and exotic supersports for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain roads.
In addition to main narrative thread also appears a thread of parallel challenges, that is, there are races in specific places that you will get to know by the stories.
Here you will get not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which serves both challenges and stories.
Upon reaching the top level, the driver opens up several possibilities, starting with the car and ending with funds for the profile.
At the same time, an online Autolog feature is connected, which compares your results with those of other players and makes other community features available.
One of the most difficult elements to understand is how the last race in history is made.
By car you get to the metro tunnel (pass), where you get to run in the dark through the tracks (pass).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and, suddenly, behind you comes the convoy of the metro and takes you ahead without further ado.
In the drafting we will surely have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the programming of the game no one even thought a little or if the real authors take us for a panda of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the general visual effects result in most pleasant cases, sometimes even superb.
It is a pity that in the most tense moments the image quality is reduced and, sometimes, in a serious way.
This particularly affects accidents where many participants are involved, when continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In order to please most of the youth group, the soundtrack belongs to the "each of his father and mother" category, but it can be assumed that no one would buy the game just for their music.
The final feel of Need for Speed: The Run is quite confusing.
If the game avoids absolutely stupid mistakes, we’d have trouble claiming that The Run is the best NFS game of recent years.
It feels like the game is not over.
The fun is assured, but get ready because mistakes will hit you in the eyes with the strength of airport reflectors.
