Innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone was looking for a term that would define IBM’s strategy with great precision, the most approximate would be “long term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet has already been a hundred years since its founding.
The basis of this platonic character was laid by the first head of the firm, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his seal, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully raised corporate culture.
“For us, IBM involves long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to thrive even more in our second century,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, current director of the company.
A sophisticated system
Watson, already in the 1930s, took care of his employees as the Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a businessman in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were the first U.S. operators to enjoy paid vacations, safe, elegant uniforms and a sophisticated remuneration system that rewarded the best inventors and sellers.
