How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 in Czechoslovakia there were only five authorized state travel agencies: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, as trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore on holiday to the beaches of the DDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned west and Czech tourists' travel was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise, individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but one had to put on a queue with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "well-known" in the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without exchange guarantee, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way the Czechs travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the DRC or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that the current favourite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European countries, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not get tired of excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to bring with them food (preserves, pastries, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it also average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in the demand for travel agencies began, starting in 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare travel using charter flights, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, and went to Thailand.
From that year onwards, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart to far and hot countries every year. This winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in their history, Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head on trips abroad, including on-site expenses.
