7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Missed Interview Showed at a Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford—distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been debunked as an advance to a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonki of flow charts – a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists in thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringley was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds on the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively on his new computer company NeXT, awaiting the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely’s interview was used on Nerds, he said the interview’s originals disappeared during their transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full copy on VHS was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly re-edited archive material is the basis of Steve Jobs: The Lost 68-Minute Interview, which arrives at Landmark Cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for precision.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringley’s questions, prompting him to move faster toward topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod, or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
One thing is to read posthumous reviews of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the dreamer looking forward to the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how he learned how to run a business:
“Over the years in business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers that invariably give you are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs brings to the detail his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Disconcerted by the way costs were recorded—often starting with a "standard cost" that was made to the eye of a good cover, and then adjusted with a "variable"—he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine commercial costs in detail.
The Pope's Joke:
Jobs recounts the “Blue Box” he built himself with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and yelling through the public phone and a minute later I came back to the public phone from the door next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us, we didn’t know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues describing a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two exploded in rushes just before the Pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and phone sales with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, in search of spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone guide and made a call.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated its employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for it.
About improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Early in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of baseplates, a customer asked him if he could assemble the whole team.
Working with only 30 credit days, he had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in the development of a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On the big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s revival, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble into his vision, and lose control of his market share.
“He says you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, so what?”
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it’s these kinds of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision-making.
The genius of the products that led to that position of monopoly is tainted by people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the victory's defeat.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t make electrons do, glass does them, robots do them, factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end, it all comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to which you are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What in part made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were accidentally the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, I might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas Dinner with Health Care Law Rivals While Court Accepts Case
The day the Supreme Court met in private to discuss the politically controversial issue of whether they would accept the challenge to President Obama’s health care law, two of its judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were entertained at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will expose the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a war cry for conservative activists across the country.
The judges agreed to file the lawsuit and, in fact, a five-and-a-half-hour historic claim is expected by March, and the result is likely to further turmoil the 2012 presidential race, which will be at its peak by the time the court’s decision becomes known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and claim that the law should be discarded will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement’s law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the Federalist Society’s annual dinner, a group that has been dedicated to advocating conservative legal principles for many years.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Businesses.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel, hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees were, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most important Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health care law.
Special guests for dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
It’s nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it is not something that conflicts with ethical norms.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct that governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, they could be said to fall under the Canon 4C Code, which says: “A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related organizations and others, although the judge may not be a speaker, an honorary guest, or appear on the program of such an event.”
However, Scalia’s absolute closeness to two of the law firms in the case, as well as to a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
“This impressive gap in ethics and indifference to the code goes against the demands of several judges that the court adheres to the same rules that apply to all federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were entertained in a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have pending cases in court."
Their appearance and assistance in raising funds for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say they too easily mix court activity with the agenda driven by groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas's wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, the Conservatives argue that it is Justice Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as attorney general of the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were presented in the court of first instance.
His critics have pressed for Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in defending the law as it is now being impartial.
Kagan has not given any indication that he will.
Boeing Receives Record Order of $18 Billion
Emirates has ordered 50 Boeing 777 double-aisle aircraft, with an option for 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliner aircraft to Oman Air, an operation valued at more than $1 billion.
Rarely is news when a company gets an order of 50 units of its product.
But it’s a big deal when the company is the aircraft manufacturer Boeing Co. and the selling price for the 50 planes is a record $18 billion.
It is as large as the place where Boeing received the order: Middle East, a growing gold mine for future aircraft orders.
