"We're all in this together."
“So anyone who can help Europe get out of the crisis is useful,” he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Bombay.
“Asia can be protected to some extent, but it can’t be immune.”
"So if China and India can help, let it be by all means."
The European monetary union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy’s debt costs have skyrocketed dangerously and Prime Ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The current sovereign debt crisis in Europe has heightened fears that it could push the global economy into recession and has generated calls for major emerging economies to join forces to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any Asian support would be channelled through the IMF, but said bilateral assistance — such as the purchase of bonds from the EU's bailout fund, the European Financial Stability Fund — offered greater bargaining power to Europe's Asian partners.
