Serious warnings from the Pentagon about possible defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta warmed Congress on Monday, warning that the impending automatic budget cuts could undermine national security and trigger a chain financial reaction from the Pentagon corridors, to Afghanistan’s battlefields, to civilian assembly chains.
The Pentagon is already digging $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 billion or more in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
“The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department,” Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, a Republican for Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, a Republican for South Carolina.
He said Congress's failure to reach an agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called "abduction," would result in 23 percent global cuts and a halt to many new projects.
“Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate way, would make most of our naval and construction projects impossible to execute – you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or a building – and seriously damage other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote.
“We would also be forced to remove many of our civil servants involuntarily, and because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to lay off civilians in order to meet the goal.”
“These changes would break the faith with those who maintain our army and seriously damage the goodwill.”
The cuts would eventually reach combat troops, Panetta said.
“While funding for wartime contingency operations accounts is not directly affected by the kidnapping, war efforts would be negatively affected by serious disruptions to basic budgets,” Panetta warned.
"The hiring of personnel would be reduced, which would lead to delays in contracts and oversight of the war-supporting contract."
"The payroll staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in payments to suppliers in time of war, and legal and political support would be disrupted."
