How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines shows us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each party accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually abetting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “picked” with an open microphone telling U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weiner made the ridicule with his denials quickly repelled by the irrefutable test.
Former Presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of infractions in campaign funding related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one living it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton in lying during his second term of office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating in school and university exams are very widespread.
There have been instances where teachers have given test responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find ourselves?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That’s for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or “locating lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: “I have you,” detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lies have been refuted.
The liars do look in the eyes.
They don’t always sneeze, sneeze, rub or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, the microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and the times.
I spent several years surveying scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if its professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies," while women tell more lies "oriented towards others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often than married people to their spouses.
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline".
It helps to provide benchmarks to measure changes afterwards.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally hits your foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when they see your feet hitting in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for deceptive, verbal and non-verbal groups of behavior.
Consider these groups of behavior as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview unhook” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change once all the difficult questions are over.
Questionnaires often falsely show that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his leg to the bottom and used the past time as he claimed his murdered wife was alive, launching a national search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... to what I know... to my understanding."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
