Quintet included the country on its two-decade-long celebration tour
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to deliver one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the band assures that for them it will also make the dream of playing in the country a reality.
This was assured by bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is on the South American wing of its two-decade-long celebration tour and Sunday 20 will make its only stop in Central America.
That day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., alongside the band Angelina The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, whose full transcript is on The Nation on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, it’s a dream come true that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are living through?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I have only been in Costa Rica once and on vacation; it is such a beautiful country and I think we will be able to stay there for a few days.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I wonder because there is a kind of devotion to the band, fans live with intensity the days before.
What do you tell your most ardent followers?
Thank you for staying with us through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the past 21 years have happened over the past couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to go surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we learned, through people who love surfing.
Upon seeing the tour, they have come to deliver huge shows with many songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we’ve never touched there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's this all about?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and each one likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we might have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it makes it more interesting for people as well.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve accomplished?
Yeah, absolutely.
First of all, I don’t think any of us would imagine we’d be in a big rock band and having done it for more than 20 years ago would sound like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and we are so excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and love to create music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean to you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of that group of great bands.
We are very friends of the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is something unusual.
From time to time, a band emerges from a city, but it’s much more strange when five or ten bands come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to be friends with them all yet and we’re honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It is also very strange that a band like yours stays united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much longer than many bands last.
Firstly, I think we are all lucky to be still alive, and secondly, we all care about others.
We are all very close friends and thanks to that, musical avenues have also been opened that give everyone freedom to experience.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do they find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don’t be too touring because it’s easy to fall into that game of great crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for music, that reminds you that you must respect music and what brought it, without capturing yourself for being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and we never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustrations because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends of Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think about the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work and have music, to laugh, to do music.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know your work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose it for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Eddie Vedder, so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to mind.
As a bassist, what are his influences?
There are so many.
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant despite not being a fashionista anymore?
I think we all always feel a bit disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time, and, if there’s relevance now, I think it’s something wonderful because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now doing better music than ever.
At first, his music had darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that may seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that qualify as very dark songs although they may sound a bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed touched me, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there’s some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
