According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n to support Uruguay in the incident with France when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the country on a list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay’s rejection and the call to consult its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the world’s most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has been in force with the South American country since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of tax exchange agreements in order to get out of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD)'s "grey list", made up of countries that did not implement all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have been in force since 2004 a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
