Asphalt from UNAM would avoid basins
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were taken care of, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 baht each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM.
In his lecture A technological view of the baches, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in his charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some northern cities of the country, to improve their performance and therefore the formation of basins.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, one of high molecular weight, called asphalts, and the other of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By passing the vehicles and generating effort, this allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, abundant, is placed a last layer called rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the rims of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction along the way.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the effort, the rolling folder also requires to have the right thickness and the material from which it is made must be cared for.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is moistened, the water diffuses inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the pavement and thus the formation of clogs.
In the process of forming a bache, he said, the first to wear is the bearing film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The National System of Investigators also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, in order to prevent the formation of bumps frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair the basins easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
