Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Interior Minister (see the May 23, Libération newspaper) declaring in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters."
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with nearly two million migrant workers", while on the left, the tone set Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take over all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande limited himself to including banalities, indicating that the co-development will allow to solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among the experts on immigration.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Concerns about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly low-skilled workers, by pressing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for domestic workers and mainly work in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthesiologists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the salaries and employment of nationals.
In light of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows means a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity provided by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the International Labour Organization estimates that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income less expenses) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points he lacked "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, from Napoleon the Little, that it was something thought.
Although universal suffrage is a necessary condition for democracy, it is not enough on its own and can even become an “instrument of oppression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we live in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return from the political sphere, but also the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its inconsistency.
We need to think about this ambivalence in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and, in many cases, the Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly way.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a vacuum of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take blows, but a common exercise, of full law, quiet and continuous, of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that folds to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, and the one that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers from humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty regains the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investments.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be made without total democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having long fought against this proposal of the Socialists and of Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
May it be so.
But thinking about it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would take us to a new dead end.
We must take a new stage in European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
An interest-driven revolution would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more integrated Europe from an economic point of view.
Only by building a more politically democratic Europe, a true European people's sovereignty, can this be achieved.
To build Europe, let's make Europe.
