The Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between orchestral music and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls the Russian gas entry into Western Europe’s network.
With this new gas pipeline, every year 27.5 million cubic meters of additional Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe through a first 1,224-kilometer tunnel that connects the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012, which will allow a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas to be supplied, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, we are already talking about the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic States had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the land flow by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
At one point, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, given that the project has generated a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to bring its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves, to success.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically,” Fillon confirmed during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom’s executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to end measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as much as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was envisaged in Swedish waters, but the project leaders resigned when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state company to permanently settle at sea off its coast.
“In case of failure, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have predicted joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to run for fifty years without the need for any kind of repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is especially favourable.
Gazprom then leased to the company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, the full gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline has been completed in 30% with the contribution of shareholders and in 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the construction is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the exit gate of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
The total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
