Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of Disabled Persons begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among people with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Desensitizer?
“No,” says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
“The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable.
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It should be noted that disabled people continue to face numerous barriers to accessing employment.
They usually have an older age: 37% are over 50 years old (on average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed their bachelor’s degree and out of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the working world and that “constitute the quid of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
