In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mindset advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprenre association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have “a low level of knowledge about disabilities,” with “excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities.”
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set out in a 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“We now reach around 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59.000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated a lot of pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
